THE Minister for Finance and Planning Dr Mwigulu Nchemba has appealed to Global Fund to support Tanzania with medical equipment so as to keep pace with the government's efforts of constructing   health infrastructure to improve service delivery. Dr Nchemba made the appeal in Dar es Salaam when he met and held talks with Head of the Global Fund High Impact Africa II Department Mr Linden Morrison who is in the country for a working tour. "The sixth phase government has invested heavily in the construction of dispensaries, health centers and hospitals which are being built countrywide but we need also to have medical equipment so that we can go with the pace of infrastructure construction," Dr Nchemba said. The minister said that the President Samia Suluhu Hassan has directed the Ministry of Finance and Planning to seek financial resources to purchase medical equipment that will have the same status with currently facilities under construction in order to provide better health care to citizens nearby their locations. Similarly, Dr Nchemba expressed gratitude to the Global Fund for providing US $ 721 million as relief fund to address the effects of Covid 19 for a period of three years from January 2021 to December 2023. He also credited the Global Fund for its intention to make Tanzania a medical tourism center whereby people from all over the world will come to the country for treatment and also to be part of the medical tourism. On the same occasion, the Head of the Global Fund Africa Department Mr Linden Morrison has commended Tanzania for partnering with global Fund in the fight against Tuberculosis, Malaria and AIDS as well as Covid 19 disease. He pledged that the Fund will continue to support the government's efforts to address the diseases in the country by directing financial resources to purchase medicines as well as improving health care systems including improving Medical Stores Department (MSD) service delivery systems and Tanzania Medicines and Medical Devices Authority (TMDA) Since the Global Fund began working with Tanzania to fight against Tuberculosis, Malaria and AIDS in 2002 to date, the Fund has provided US $ 1.9 billion.